hcache. It's tricky, as I could only use one qualified version or rename it. Maybe I should focus on using `SessionFactoryImpl` instead of a fake class to streamline things. I'll need to keep things clean and functional!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Creating a Real Factory**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how to create a real factory using Hibernate's `SessionFactory`. I know I need to set various properties like dialect and cache provider in my configuration. However, I'm running into an issue because version 3.5's `SessionFactory` interface doesn't have the `getProperties` method, but `SessionFactoryImpl` does. I might need to cast to `SessionFactoryImpl` to access its properties.\\n\\nIt's essential to handle closing properly without running the build, especially since the user requested not to compile or run tests themselves. I need to ensure the implementation remains clean and functional without unnecessary complexity!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing Hibernate Configuration**\\n\\nI'm considering how the SessionFactory registers itself and the importance of closing instances properly. It seems like enabling MBean with `HibernateStatsImpl(sessionFactory)` is working well. I ponder the idea of throwing a fake out to keep the file size smaller, maybe rewriting it to make things easier. \\n\\nI need to avoid name conflicts, possibly by qualifying imports. But there's a question here: Can I import conflicting classes? Searching existing files may provide some insight.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_jGa7eg4L7syxPFn5nJcDYFco|fc_0b9fb158509d5c490169f5633b0cac81a0b1d79c6dd22d0994", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"new org\\.\" tests/src/net.sf.ehcache/ehcache-core/2.4.4/src/test/java -n | head"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 424, "output": 1414, "cacheRead": 31744, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 33582, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWr